✦ Finding historical flood data can be exciting but a bit overwhelming at first. Here are the best sources for beginners,
  broken down by what they cover and how you can use them:

  1. Dartmouth Flood Observatory (DFO)
   * What it covers: Global floods from 1985 to the present day. It's one of the most famous long-term lists of floods
     around the world.
   * Format: It usually comes as an Excel (.xls) or CSV file (which works like a spreadsheet).
   * How to access: Go to the DFO Global Archive (https://floodobservatory.colorado.edu/Archives/index.html) and look for
     the "Master Index." This file has columns for "Centroid X" (Longitude) and "Centroid Y" (Latitude), which represent
     the middle point of each flood event.

  2. USGS Flood Event Viewer (USA only)
   * What it covers: Detailed flood data across the United States, with some records going back as far as 1888. 
   * Format: It’s an Interactive Map. You can also download data for specific events as CSV or GeoJSON files (a common map
     data format).
   * How to access: Visit the USGS Viewer (https://stn.wim.usgs.gov/fev/). You can click on specific flood events (like a
     major hurricane) and see "High Water Marks" where the water reached its highest point.

  3. Global Flood Database (by Floodbase)
   * What it covers: This uses satellite images to show the actual "footprint" of 913 major flood events between 2000 and
     2018. It’s great if you want to see the shape of the flooded area, not just a single point.
   * Format: Raster data (basically a picture where each pixel tells you if it was flooded or not).
   * How to access: It is hosted on Google Earth Engine
     (https://developers.google.com/earth-engine/datasets/catalog/GLOBAL_FLOOD_DB_MODIS_EVENTS_V1). Since you're a
     beginner, you can use their Interactive Map Tool (https://global-flood-database.cloudtostreet.ai/) to browse the data
     without needing to write any code.

  4. EM-DAT (The International Disaster Database)
   * What it covers: Large-scale natural disasters (including floods) worldwide since 1900. It focuses more on the impact
     (like people affected or damage costs) rather than exact map shapes.
   * Format: Excel or CSV.
   * How to access: You can create a free account on the EM-DAT website (https://www.emdat.be/) and search their database.
     While it provides the country and region, you might need to combine it with another tool if you want exact
     coordinates.

  A Quick Tip for Beginners:
  If you download a CSV file with Latitude and Longitude columns, you can upload it directly to Google My Maps
  (https://www.google.com/maps/about/mymaps/) to see all those flood events on a map instantly—no special software
  required!



