✦ For creating a Leaflet map, the best format from that list depends on what kind of data you want to show:

  1. The "Easiest" Overall: XLSX (Excel)
  If you just want to put markers on a map (points for each flood), use the XLSX file. 
   * Why: You can open it in Excel, check that it has columns for Latitude and Longitude, and then save it as a CSV file.
   * How to use with Leaflet: You can use a small library like PapaParse (https://www.papaparse.com/) to read the CSV file
     and add markers to your map in just a few lines of code.

  2. The "Best" for High Quality: SHP (Shapefile)
  If you want to show the actual shapes of the flooded areas (polygons), the SHP file is the standard.
   * Why: It contains the exact boundaries of the floods, not just a single center point.
   * How to use with Leaflet: Leaflet doesn't "read" Shapefiles directly, but it loves GeoJSON. You can take that SHP file
     and quickly convert it to a GeoJSON file using a free online tool like Mapshaper (https://mapshaper.org/). Once it's
     a .json file, Leaflet can display those shapes perfectly.

  Summary:
   * Go with XLSX/CSV if you are just starting out and want simple markers.
   * Go with SHP (and convert to GeoJSON) if you want to see the real areas that were flooded on your map.
